LAFIA  – National Locust Beans Producers, Processors Marketers’ Association of Nigeria (NALBPPMAN) has trained over 2,000 indigenes in manufacturing and processing of locust beans in Nasarawa State. The Nasarawa State Coordinator of the organization, Rhoda Sunday, disclosed at a one-day training and sensitization on locust beans production, processing and marketing/exhibition in Lafia, the state capital. She said that the sensitization awareness was to equip participants on how to improve the variety and how to process and sell to the consumer. -Advertisement- Sunday explained that the plan does not need fertilizer to grow, adding that what is needed to grow locust beans is the use of local manure. “Nigerians should take advantage of the improved variety because of its economic benefit and health benefit, as it’s highly recommended and needed in the world market today. Also speaking, a clinical nutritionist, Dr. Thomas Affi, listed the health benefits of locust beans to include: 29 percent fat, 35 percent protein, 16 per cent carbohydrate, and very rich in calcium. Dr. Afi also explained that the oil in locust bean is unsaturated oleic acid, which prevents cancer of the breast and is 100 per cent more powerful than any other oil in prolonging life. On his part, the state Commissioner for the Environment and Natural Resources, Kwanta Yakubu, frowned at the indiscriminate deforestation, warning against further cutting of economic trees, which is exposing the state to environmental hazard and reducing economic benefit of the forest. POLL Kwanta, who was represented by director in the ministry, Angbashim Ishaku, called for planting of more economic trees.